Exploratory Data Analysis Example

Scenario

A self-insured company wants to identify if providing managed care to their employees and covered dependents improves the overall health of their covered members.

  • Without the availability of clinical notes from the hospitals to capture actual health outcomes, they use a proxy to aim at capturing the overall health as the total amount of billed charges from hospital, office, urgent, and emergency room visits.
  • The company provides 2016 - 2018 data grouped by individual by year and includes various demographic indicators, frequency of visits to health practitioners, number of diseases, count of pharmacy scrips and if the patient was diagnosed with a serious disease in the indicated year.1 30 features are: year, CGI, Age, isMale, MM, Employee, Spouse, Admission, ALOS, ERVisit, OutERVisit, OV, LongOV, UrgentCare, NumDis, NumChronic, NumAcute, NumScripts, Billed, Cancer, Type2, Type1, Hypertension, CAD, CHF, Cerebro, RenalFail, MajorTrauma, Premature, Transplant
    • 2016 should have 52,353 records
    • 2017 should have 54,124 records
    • 2018 should have 56,956 records
  • To identify the validity of managed care, they also have access to the number of ‘Care Gaps’2 CGI feature in the data the members had over the course of the year, which they define as the number of times an individual does not meet clinical guidelines for care based on his/her diagnosed diseases or for preventive care.

Read the data

df <- read_csv('finaldata.csv') %>%
  mutate(rn = row_number()) %>%
  select(rn, everything())

Just skimming through the structure I see one NA in Spouse, but the data formatted as numbers makes sense as the descriptive variables are already coded to binary.

Check the missing values

# # identify variables with missing data
df %>% 
  select_if(function(x) any(is.na(x))) %>% 
  summarise_each(funs(sum(is.na(.))))
## # A tibble: 1 x 4
##   Spouse Cancer Type2 Type1
##    <int>  <int> <int> <int>
## 1  11975   1072  1072  1072

Spouse has 11,975 NAs. Cancer, Type1, and Type2 each have 1,072.

To try to determine if there’s any similarities across the missing variables, I’ll try to compare against the two demographic variables available - Age and isMale.

# # baseline for comparison
baseline <- summary(df %>% 
          select(Age, isMale))

print(baseline)

Spouse looks to be missing only when the person’s age is under 17. This would seem to be MNAR (Missing Not at Random); however, it would be intuitive there would not be spouses under the age of 18 on the health plan. For now I will recode this binary variable as 0, rather than missing, and will follow up with the company to validate.5 Follow up with data provider to verify there are no spouses under 18

# # recode Spouse to 0 when 17 or less
df %<>% 
  mutate(Spouse = case_when(Age<=17 ~ 0,
                            TRUE ~ Spouse))
print(baseline)

Check distributions and look for outliers

df %>% select(-rn, -year) %>% 
  tidyr::gather(var, value) %>%
  ggplot(aes(value)) +
  geom_density() +
  facet_wrap(~var, scales='free', ncol=1)

Most of these variables look very, very right skewed. Boxplots may show more information:

df %>% 
  select(-rn, -year) %>%
  tidyr::gather(var, value) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.factor(var), y=value)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(~var, scales='free', ncol=1)

There are quite a bit of outliers, so we may need to research these to identify how to handle.

Try the easy solution first

The data provider hypothesizes that the number of Care Gaps an individual has will be directly predicting of the billed charges.

df %>% 
  select(CGI, Billed) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.factor(CGI), y=Billed)) +
  geom_boxplot()

There does appear to be evidence to support that higher CGI predicts higher billed charges.

Check all variables for potential collinearities

df %>% 
  select(-rn, -year) %>%
  cor %>%
  corrplot
